";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"MonsterInsights Permissions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"Google Analytics user permissions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34:\"Google Analytics permission levels\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=174329\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:659:\"<p>Want to learn how to use and manage user permissions in Google Analytics? Understanding user permissions is crucial while sharing access to your Google Analytics account or data with other people as it concerns with the safety, privacy, and the overall growth strategies of your business(es). In this article, we’ll explain everything you need to [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/beginners-guide-to-user-permissions-in-google-analytics/\">Beginner&#8217;s Guide to User Permissions in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17373:\"<p>Want to learn how to use and manage user permissions in Google Analytics? Understanding user permissions is crucial while sharing access to your Google Analytics account or data with other people as it concerns with the safety, privacy, and the overall growth strategies of your business(es). </p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll explain everything you need to know about Google Analytics user permissions and how to manage them easily. </p>\n<h3>What Are User Permissions in Google Analytics?</h3>\n<p>In Google Analytics, you can add other people from your team as users and allow them access to your Analytics account or data at different levels. Such different levels of access to your Analytics account or data are called ‘user permissions’. User permissions refer to the types of privileges a user gets in a Google Analytics account.</p>\n<p>For example, you as the owner of your Analytics account can view all the data, add, edit, and manage website properties, add users and manage them. However, you may not want to give the same level of access to another person. That’s what user permissions are designed for. </p>\n<p>User permissions allow you to provide a certain level of access to certain users. Using them, you can <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-grant-access-to-your-account-and-share-google-analytics-reports/\">grant access to your Analytics data and share useful reports</a>. </p>\n<p>Thus you should carefully decide whom you want to give editing access, managing access, or view only access. User permissions help you to share data while also ensuring your full control over your account management and data usage.</p>\n<p>Google Analytics allows you to provide 4 types of user permissions at 3 levels. Let’s first start with the permission levels.</p>\n<h3>Google Analytics Permission Levels</h3>\n<p>Google Analytics lets you provide permissions at 3 different levels of your Google Analytics account. The levels of user permissions are based on the hierarchical structure of Google Analytics organization.  </p>\n<p><strong>1. Account Level</strong></p>\n<p>An account is the top-most level of organization which can include multiple properties (websites) and multiple views. </p>\n<p>Providing access at account level means allowing access to all the properties and views in your account. </p>\n<p><strong>2. Property Level</strong></p>\n<p>A property is typically a website. There can be multiple views under one property. </p>\n<p>For example, all website data for https://yoursite.com can be one view whereas only traffic to the subdomain https://blog.yoursite.com can be another view.  </p>\n<p>Providing access at property level means allowing access to all the views in your property/website.</p>\n<p><strong>3. View Level</strong></p>\n<p>A view is a subset of an Analytics account property. It allows access to only a defined view of data from a website property. </p>\n<p>For example; you may want to allow access to only the subdomain view i.e. https://blog.yoursite.com to a content writer in your team. </p>\n<p>That’s why you’ll see <strong>User Management</strong> option in all three levels of your Analytics admin options. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels.jpg\" alt=\"user-management-ga-3-levels\" width=\"620\" height=\"292\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174342\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels-300x141.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<h3>Types of Google Analytics User Permissions</h3>\n<p>There&#8217;re 4 types of user permissions you can provide at each level discussed above.<br />\n<strong>1. Manage Users</strong></p>\n<p>Users with this permission can perform following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Add and delete users</li>\n<li>Manage users and grant full permissions to anyone including themselves</li>\n</ul>\n<p>However this permission doesn’t include edit or collaborate permissions. </p>\n<p><strong>2. Edit</strong></p>\n<p>Users with <strong>Edit</strong> permission can perform following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Add, edit, and delete accounts, properties, and views as per the permission level</li>\n<li>Add, edit, and delete goals</li>\n<li>Create/ edit custom dimensions and metrics (Edit permission at property level is required)</li>\n<li>Connect Adwords, Search Console, and other products (Edit permission at property level is required)</li>\n<li>Add, edit, and delete filters (Edit permission at account level permission is required)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It includes all permissions from <strong>Collaborate</strong> and <strong>Read and Analyze</strong> permissions but not <strong>Manage Users</strong> permissions. </p>\n<p><strong>3. Collaborate</strong></p>\n<p>Users with <strong>Collaborate</strong> permission can perform the following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Create, edit, delete, and share personal assets</li>\n<li>Collaborate on shared assets like custom reports, dashboards, segments, etc. </li>\n</ul>\n<p>It includes all permissions from <strong>Read and Analyze</strong> but not <strong>Manage Users</strong> and <strong>Edit</strong> permissions. </p>\n<p><strong>4.Read and Analyze</strong></p>\n<p>Users with this permission can perform following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>View reports</li>\n<li>Manipulate data within reports like filtering a table, adding secondary dimension, create a segment, etc.</li>\n<li>See shared assets however cannot collaborate on them.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It doesn’t include any of the permissions discussed above. </p>\n<h3>Understanding Permission Types at Permission Levels</h3>\n<p>The users can perform actions on only the levels for which they have these permissions. For example, if a user is allowed <strong>Manage Users</strong> permission at <strong>Account</strong> level, they can add, manage, and delete users in the account, in all website properties, and views. However a user with <strong>Manage Users</strong> permission at <strong>View</strong> level can add, manage, and delete users for only 1 view they’ve permission for. </p>\n<p>Normally you may not want to allow <strong>Manage Users</strong> or <strong>Edit</strong> permission at <strong>Account</strong> level to anyone except your business partner with equal share.</p>\n<h3>How to Add Users and Manage Permissions in Google Analytics?</h3>\n<p>Now that you know user permissions and levels, you may want to know how to add users and manage permissions. Next, we’ll show you how to do that. </p>\n<p>To get started, you’ll need to sign in to your Google Analytics account. Then, click <strong>Admin</strong> option at the bottom of your Analytics panel in the left.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg\" alt=\"ga-admin\" width=\"250\" height=\"586\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169257\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg 250w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin-128x300.jpg 128w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 250px) 100vw, 250px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, you’ll see the 3 levels of access i.e. Account, Property, and View. And, you’ll also find <strong>User Management</strong> option below all 3 access levels. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels.jpg\" alt=\"user-management-ga-3-levels\" width=\"620\" height=\"292\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174342\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/user-management-ga-3-levels-300x141.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Navigate to your desired level Account or Property or View and click the <strong>User Management</strong> option. </p>\n<p>Then, you’ll see the list of users with a brief summary of the permissions allowed to them. </p>\n<p>Click the <strong>+ (Plus)</strong> icon to add new users. Select <strong>Add New Users</strong> option. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-user-ga.jpg\" alt=\"add-new-user-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"193\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174343\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-user-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-new-user-ga-300x93.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, you’ll see a new page where you can add new users and assign permissions. </p>\n<p>First, enter the email address you want to add. If you want to add multiple users with the same type of permissions, you can enter the email addresses separated by the comma. </p>\n<p>Select <strong>Notify new users by email</strong> option. And, select the permissions you want to allow. Then, click the <strong>Add</strong> button. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-permissions-ga.jpg\" alt=\"add-permissions-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"469\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174344\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-permissions-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/add-permissions-ga-300x227.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>That’s it! You’ve successfully added a new user(s) to your Analytics account. Now they’ll be able to view, edit, collaborate or manage users in your Analytics account as per the permissions you provided. </p>\n<h3>How to Edit and Delete Users in Google Analytics?</h3>\n<p>If you want to edit any user’s permissions, you can go to the list of users by navigating to <strong>Admin &raquo; User Management</strong> from Account, Property or View level. </p>\n<p>Then, navigate to the user’s name in the list you want to edit and click on it. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-users-ga.jpg\" alt=\"edit-users-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"208\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174345\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-users-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/edit-users-ga-300x101.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>After that, you can select and deselect user permissions as you like. Once you add or remove permissions, click the <strong>Save</strong> button. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-user-permissions-ga.jpg\" alt=\"save-user-permissions-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"538\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174346\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-user-permissions-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/save-user-permissions-ga-300x260.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>If you want to remove the user, you can click the <strong>Remove</strong> button next to the <strong>Save</strong> button. </p>\n<p>If you want to delete multiple users at once, you can go to the list of users from <strong>Admin &raquo; User Management</strong>. Then, select the users you want to delete and click the <strong>Remove</strong> button at the top of right side. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/remove-users-ga.jpg\" alt=\"remove-users-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"206\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-174349\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/remove-users-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/remove-users-ga-300x100.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<h3>EASY Way to Managing User Permissions in WordPress</h3>\n<p>The easiest way to manage your Google Analytics user permissions in WordPress is using <strong>Permissions</strong> option in <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> plugin. </p>\n<p>The MonsterInsights Permissions allows you to assign your WordPress users the permissions to view reports and save settings in Google Analytics dashboard reports inside WordPress. And you can do that in just 2 easy clicks of your mouse.</p>\n<p>However, this method is exclusively useful only for WordPress sites that are using MonsterInsights to use Google Analytics. </p>\n<p>So before we show you the steps, you&#8217;ll need to make sure that you’ve connected your site with your Google Analytics account using MonsterInsights. If you need instructions, here’s our step-by-step guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">how to properly set up Google Analytics in WordPress using MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve completed the setup process, you can go to <strong>Insights &raquo; Settings</strong> and click the <strong>Tracking</strong> tab. Then, scroll down to the end where you’ll find <strong>Permissions</strong> section. Click on that.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-171106\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-permissions-settings.jpg\" alt=\"mi-permissions-settings\" width=\"620\" height=\"700\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-permissions-settings.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-permissions-settings-266x300.jpg 266w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you can allow permissions to view your Google Analytics reports and save settings to the selected user roles.</p>\n<p>All you need to do to share access to see the reports is to select the user roles.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-171107\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-allow-permission-to-view-ga-reports.jpg\" alt=\"mi-allow-permission-to-view-ga-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"404\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-allow-permission-to-view-ga-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-allow-permission-to-view-ga-reports-300x195.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Similarly, select the user roles whom you want to grant access to both view and save settings.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-171108\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-let-users-save-settings.jpg\" alt=\"mi-let-users-save-settings\" width=\"620\" height=\"531\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-let-users-save-settings.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mi-let-users-save-settings-300x257.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, don’t forget to hit <strong>Save Changes</strong>.</p>\n<p>That’s it! Now your selected user roles (administrators, editors, authors, or other user roles) will get access to your Google Analytics dashboard reports and settings by going to <strong>Insights</strong> menu in the WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p><strong>A Few Words About MonsterInsights</strong></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-157422\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress\" width=\"620\" height=\"250\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress-300x121.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re wondering why would anyone want to use MonsterInsights, here&#8217;re a few words. First, it makes Google Analytics super simple for WordPress website owners. It lets you install and use Google Analytics in WordPress effortlessly.</p>\n<p>Second, the plugin helps you to track your most important Google Analytics metrics and provides you with the extremely comprehensive reports. Best of all, you can view all your <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/feature/google-analytics-dashboard/\">reports right in your WordPress dashboard</a> without having to navigate away to other sites.</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s the most popular, user-friendly Google Analytics WordPress plugin available on the market. </p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you learn about Google Analytics user permissions and how to manage them.</p>\n<p>You may also want to learn <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-share-your-google-analytics-reports-with-others/\">how to share your Google Analytics reports with others</a>.</p>\n<p>Don’t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more Google Analytics tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/beginners-guide-to-user-permissions-in-google-analytics/\">Beginner&#8217;s Guide to User Permissions in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\"