(99, 1, '2018-12-08 01:18:08', '2018-12-08 09:18:08', 'This is a concept for a neighbourhood butcher, fishmonger and delicatessen. The logo is all about the background, the Hunting MacPherson tartan.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"wp-image-104 alignnone\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/tartan-banner@3x-300x38.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"497\" height=\"63\" />\r\n\r\nA tartan is traditional, something with a history, not necessarily seen as current today, but people who claim a tartan still take pride in it. I am of Scottish descent myself, so I used my family tartan for the logo.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Butchery—particularly whole beast butchery—is also traditional, and in the age of the supermarket, not a ‘modern’ concept, but the people who still have these skills maintain an ages-old trade and take pride in their work.\r\n\r\n<img class=\" wp-image-32 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/tartan-typeface-247x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"216\" height=\"247\" />I used the Luminari display font for the store name, as it evokes the Celtic spirit. The Luminari font was developed from medieval calligraphy, like Unical, a calligraphy hand often used in relation with anything Celtic.\r\n\r\nThis design is easily adaptable to a flyer, a newspaper ad, employee shirts, or re-useable shopping bags. Run the tartan down the left side (along the fold, if it is a flyer), place a large ‘T’ at the bottom, or use  the full store name popping off the tartan stripe.', 'Tartan', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'tartan', '', '', '2018-12-10 01:08:27', '2018-12-10 09:08:27', '', 0, 'http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/?p=99', 6, 'post', '', 0),
