ged it, making it the both the pupil of the eye and something bigger, more distinct. Overlaying the ampersand on the silhouette joined the visual portion and the text portion of the logo. The last touch was turning the tail of the ampersand up and joining it to the eye outline, making the ampersand and eye outline one complete stroke.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-26 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/IEye-Final-300x232.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"232\" />', 'I & Eye Magazine', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '115-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-12-08 01:38:43', '2018-12-08 09:38:43', '', 115, 'http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/2018/12/08/115-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(118, 1, '2018-12-08 03:00:35', '2018-12-08 11:00:35', 'Really, this is a play on my initials, recalling Einstein’s familiar equation, E = mc<sup>2</sup>. While I believe most people will get the reference to the theory of relativity, but I decided to spell out the relevance of the equation to web design.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-119 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/DMc2-motto-a@3x-300x24.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"24\" />\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Design is the overall thought process behind building a website. Imagery stands for raster and vector graphics, otherwise known as photos and illustrations. Coding is squared because there are two essential languages to build a website: HTML and CSS. Without those two there can be no website. Other programming languages like JavaScript or Sass, work off either HTML or CSS or work behind the scenes, like PHP and Java. Those languages give a website utility and functionality, but without HTML and CSS there is no website on which to work.\r\n\r\nMost people have only two initials, unless they use their middle name, but as a young boy, I decided my initials were DMc. I was about six years old when I discovered that the Mc in my name was short for Mac, which means ‘son of’, and initials were the first two letters of the first and last name. If I used just two initials, my six-year-old self reasoned, the M would just stand for Murdo, and I would lose a portion of my last name, and that was unacceptable. Ever since then, I’ve written my initials as DMc.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-120 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/DMc2-typeExp-300x108.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"108\" />\r\n\r\nI gravitated to the serif fonts, as sans serif fonts seemed lacking—probably the serifs, which is the point—and I liked the formality of the serifs. The early contenders were Bookman Oldstyle, Montserrat, Noto Serif, and Sitka, but ultimately, I liked Cambria’s squared off finials on the small c.', 'D = Mc<sup>2</sup>', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'd-mc2', '', '', '2018-12-10 00:37:57', '2018-12-10 08:37:57', '', 0, 'http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/?p=118', 2, 'post', '', 0),
