(155, 1, '2018-12-10 00:37:31', '2018-12-10 08:37:31', 'This was designed for a reviving online college short story magazine. The magazine was defunct for a couple years, and wanted to re-brand as part of its renewal.\r\n\r\nIn creative writing, the author puts certain elements in a story, but readers interpret that meaning through their own experience, so I &amp; Eye was defined as the experience of the individual and the eye of the beholder.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-28 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/IEye-work1-300x232.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"232\" />\r\n\r\nI liked the concept of the two distinct viewpoints, and wanted to incorporate them into a visual whole, paying particular attention to the ampersand. I explored several different typefaces, before simplifying the text portion, going with Hoefler Text for both I and Eye, as it is easier reading, but kept Palatino’s decorative ampersand as key to the design. Both the name and concept hinged on the joining of two things, so I wanted a very decorative ampersand.\r\n\r\nI developed the concept further, finding and tracing the silhouette of a figure, creating a second eye outline, and exploring ways to work the elements together. I wanted to keep a very simple colour palette, and tried to use natural eye colours, settling on blue and green as the most accessible. Matching the word ‘magazine’ with the colour of the figure draws the text and the image of the logo together.<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-29 alignright\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/IEye-work2-300x234.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"234\" />\r\n\r\nI trimmed the concepts down to a few contenders. I really liked the idea of full figure standing in front of the eye (top centre), but it diminished the figure too much. Also, the A in ‘magazine’ was in an unfortunate position.\r\n\r\nMy final version used less of the silhouette but enlarged it, making it the both the pupil of the eye and something bigger, more distinct. Overlaying the ampersand on the silhouette joined the visual portion and the text portion of the logo. The last touch was turning the tail of the ampersand up and joining it to the eye outline, making the ampersand and eye outline one complete stroke.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-26 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/IEye-Final-300x232.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"232\" />', 'I & Eye Magazine', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '115-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-12-10 00:37:31', '2018-12-10 08:37:31', '', 115, 'http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/2018/12/10/115-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(156, 1, '2018-12-10 00:37:57', '2018-12-10 08:37:57', 'Really, this is a play on my initials, recalling Einstein’s familiar equation, E = mc<sup>2</sup>. While I believe most people will get the reference to the theory of relativity, but I decided to spell out the relevance of the equation to web design.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-119 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/DMc2-motto-a@3x-300x24.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"24\" />\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Design is the overall thought process behind building a website. Imagery stands for raster and vector graphics, otherwise known as photos and illustrations. Coding is squared because there are two essential languages to build a website: HTML and CSS. Without those two there can be no website. Other programming languages like JavaScript or Sass, work off either HTML or CSS or work behind the scenes, like PHP and Java. Those languages give a website utility and functionality, but without HTML and CSS there is no website on which to work.\r\n\r\nMost people have only two initials, unless they use their middle name, but as a young boy, I decided my initials were DMc. I was about six years old when I discovered that the Mc in my name was short for Mac, which means ‘son of’, and initials were the first two letters of the first and last name. If I used just two initials, my six-year-old self reasoned, the M would just stand for Murdo, and I would lose a portion of my last name, and that was unacceptable. Ever since then, I’ve written my initials as DMc.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-120 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/DMc2-typeExp-300x108.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"108\" />\r\n\r\nI gravitated to the serif fonts, as sans serif fonts seemed lacking—probably the serifs, which is the point—and I liked the formality of the serifs. The early contenders were Bookman Oldstyle, Montserrat, Noto Serif, and Sitka, but ultimately, I liked Cambria’s squared off finials on the small c.', 'D = Mc<sup>2</sup>', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '118-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-12-10 00:37:57', '2018-12-10 08:37:57', '', 118, 'http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/2018/12/10/118-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(157, 1, '2018-12-10 00:38:47', '2018-12-10 08:38:47', 'Konverge is a purely typographical design of a company name. I focused on the meaning of the word ‘converge’— “come together from different directions to eventually meet” according to the Oxford English Dictionary—and the idea that the company’s skill-base meets, or converges, if you will, with their client’s needs.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nI explored various fonts and ideas to express this concept:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-25 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/LogoType-300x184.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"184\" />\r\n\r\nI did get a little stuck on the idea of arrows. Initially, I liked the top centre logotype and how part of the K turned into an arrowhead, particularly because the K could then be used in isolation as a badge. However, there was only one arrow in the design, so it only gave a sense of direction instead of convergence.\r\n\r\nNext, I looked at the length of the word KONVERGE and how the middle bars of the two Es and part of the G and part of the R suggested a line extending across the word. Also, the letter V was close to the middle of the word (it would have helped me if ‘converge’ was a seven-letter word, leaving the V exactly in the middle, but I made do with the English language as it is), and the angle of the V did suggest half of an arrowhead.\r\n\r\nUsing a solid arrow concealed the company name to much, so I chose negative<img class=\"size-full wp-image-30 alignright\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Konverge-badge.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"107\" height=\"108\" /> space instead, letting the mind of the viewer fill in what wasn’t there. Adding the triangle behind the V accentuates the angles and brings the arrowhead into focus. The V overlaid on the triangle is a second convergence of arrows (just the heads this time), and, like the K-arrow, could stand alone as a badge.\r\n\r\nEither the badge or the full logotype can be used on company mugs, baseball caps, pens, or as an emblem on a polo shirt.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-31 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Konverge-logotype-300x50.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"50\" />', 'KONVERGE', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '113-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-12-10 00:38:47', '2018-12-10 08:38:47', '', 113, 'http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/2018/12/10/113-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
