(158, 1, '2018-12-10 00:39:19', '2018-12-10 08:39:19', 'This was designed for an (unfortunately) theoretical wolf sanctuary located to the north of Vancouver Island.\r\n\r\nI made several very rough sketches before developing an idea in Illustrator. I knew I needed to involve the wolf in some way, so first I traced the outline of a wolf’s head to use as a scalable vector graphic.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-35 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/RCWS-outline-300x212.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"212\" />\r\n\r\n<!--more-->The initial concept was a rocky coastline in the top right corner and a wolf’s head off the coast line in the ‘water’, but the idea didn’t convey very well.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-37 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/RCWS-roughs-300x182.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"182\" />\r\n\r\nI chose Athelas Bold, a serif font, for the sanctuary name and used Thonburi, a sans serif font, in all caps to explicitly state what Rocky Coast was.\r\n\r\nI needed to ground the logo with a better sense of place, so I resolved to incorporate Vancouver Island in the logo as well.  After outlining Vancouver Island, I switched the position of the wolf’s head, so it emerged as part of the island.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-34 alignright\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/RCWS-full-300x181.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"181\" />\r\n\r\nThis logo can be used on business cards and stationary, company vehicles, or on hats, t-shirts, sweatshirts, and jackets, or as a watermark on advertising or postcards.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-33\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/RCWF-watermark-200x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" />', 'Rocky Coast Wolf Sanctuary', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '110-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-12-10 00:39:19', '2018-12-10 08:39:19', '', 110, 'http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/2018/12/10/110-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(159, 1, '2018-12-10 00:39:55', '2018-12-10 08:39:55', 'This is a concept for a neighbourhood butcher, fishmonger and delicatessen. The logo is all about the background, the Hunting MacPherson tartan.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"wp-image-104 alignnone\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/tartan-banner@3x-300x38.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"497\" height=\"63\" />\r\n\r\nA tartan is traditional, something with a history, not necessarily seen as current today, but people who claim a tartan still take pride in it. I am of Scottish descent myself, so I used my family tartan for the logo.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Butchery—particularly whole beast butchery—is also traditional, and in the age of the supermarket, not a ‘modern’ concept, but the people who still have these skills maintain an ages-old trade and take pride in their work.\r\n\r\n<img class=\" wp-image-32 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/tartan-typeface-247x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"216\" height=\"247\" />I used the Luminari display font for the store name, as it evokes the Celtic spirit. The Luminari font was developed from medieval calligraphy, like Unical, a calligraphy hand often used in relation with anything Celtic.\r\n\r\nThis design is easily adaptable to a flyer, a newspaper ad, employee shirts, or re-useable shopping bags. Run the tartan down the left side (along the fold, if it is a flyer), place a large ‘T’ at the bottom, or use  the full store name popping off the tartan stripe.', 'Tartan Meat Fish Deli', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '99-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-12-10 00:39:55', '2018-12-10 08:39:55', '', 99, 'http://localhost/dequalsmcsquared/2018/12/10/99-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
